## Summary

I have successfully identified and fixed the bug in the `HttpConnection.java` file. Here's what I found and fixed:

### Root Cause
The bug was in the `looksLikeUtf8` method within the `Base` class of `HttpConnection.java`. The method had a buffer overflow issue when checking if a byte sequence looks like valid UTF-8.

When processing a single byte that looked like the start of a multi-byte UTF-8 sequence (like byte 0xE9 for "é"), the code would:
1. Determine it was the start of a 2-byte, 3-byte, or 4-byte UTF-8 sequence
2. Set the `end` position accordingly (e.g., `end = i + 2` for a 3-byte sequence)
3. Proceed to loop and increment `i`, then access `input[i]` without checking if `i` was within array bounds
4. This caused an `IndexOutOfBoundsException` when the array didn't have enough bytes for the complete sequence

### The Fix
I added bounds checking before calculating the UTF-8 sequence length in the `looksLikeUtf8` method:

```java
// UTF-8 leading:
if ((o & 0xE0) == 0xC0) {
    // 110xxxxx - needs 1 more byte
    if (i + 1 >= j) return false; // not enough bytes remaining
    end = i + 1;
} else if ((o & 0xF0) == 0xE0) {
    // 1110xxxx - needs 2 more bytes
    if (i + 2 >= j) return false; // not enough bytes remaining
    end = i + 2;
} else if ((o & 0xF8) == 0xF0) {
    // 11110xxx - needs 3 more bytes
    if (i + 3 >= j) return false; // not enough bytes remaining
    end = i + 3;
} else {
    return false;
}
```

### Verification
- The triggering test `org.jsoup.helper.HttpConnectionTest::handlesHeaderEncodingOnRequest` now passes
- All other relevant tests continue to pass
- The fix correctly handles the character "é" and other cases that could cause buffer overflows

The patch file `blind_fix.patch` contains the exact changes needed to fix this issue.

